          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a smooth scheme of finite type over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
    The construction of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.2.xml" number="4.4.2" /> establishes an equivalence of categories between

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        the category of abelian schemes over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>; and
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        the category of polarisable continuous families of Hodge structures <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-1,0)+(0,-1)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> is torsion free and the Hodge filtration varies holomorphically on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1669</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#281</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-281.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The essential surjectivity of the functor that goes from (a) to (b) follows from Borel (<fr:em>unpublished</fr:em>);
      the full faithfulness follows from the fact that, for two abelian schemes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_2]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>-scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\underline {\operatorname {Hom}}_S(X_1,X_2)]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, and thus has the same algebraic and holomorphic sections.</fr:p>
